      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>GABA (Gamma-Aminobutyric Acid)</strong>
        <p>The brain's primary inhibitory neurotransmitter. Supplemental GABA promotes relaxation by dampening excessive neural excitation. Works within 30-60 minutes at 100-200mg doses. Most effective in combination with L-Theanine, which enhances GABA receptor sensitivity.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Lemon Balm (Melissa officinalis)</strong>
        <p>A member of the mint family with centuries of traditional use for nervous tension. Modern research shows it inhibits GABA-transaminase, increasing available GABA in the brain. A 2014 study found 300mg significantly reduced anxiety and improved mood within 1 hour. Well-tolerated with minimal side effects.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>Magnesium</strong>
        <p>An essential mineral involved in 300+ enzymatic reactions, including HPA axis regulation. Deficiency amplifies the cortisol stress response. Magnesium glycinate is the preferred form for stress because it crosses the blood-brain barrier and doubles as a GABA receptor agonist. Often included as a supporting ingredient in stress formulas.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="info-card">
        <strong>B-Complex Vitamins</strong>
        <p>B vitamins (especially B6, B12, and folate) are cofactors in neurotransmitter synthesis, including serotonin and GABA production. Chronic stress depletes B vitamin stores. A 2011 meta-analysis found B-complex supplementation reduced perceived stress and improved mood in healthy adults under occupational pressure.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

